  <title>ideal mixture</title>
  <termversion>2.3.3</termversion>
  <lastupdated>2014-02-24</lastupdated>
  <definitions>
    <item>
      <id>1</id>
      <text>A mixture of substances B, C, ... is called an ideal mixture when aB = xB, aC = xC, ... or fB = 1, fC = 1 where aB and fB are the relative activity and the activity coefficient, respectively, of a substance B in a liquid or solid mixture.</text>
      <links>
        <item>
          <title>relative activity</title>
          <url>https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/R05256</url>
        </item>
        <item>
          <title>activity coefficient</title>
          <url>https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/A00116</url>
        </item>
      </links>
      <math>
        <item>
          <meaning>Chemical activity (in ideal mixture)</meaning>
          <type>math</type>
          <alttext>aB = xB</alttext>
          <latex>a_{\text{B}}=x_{\text{B}}</latex>
        </item>
        <item>
          <meaning>Chemical activity (in ideal mixture)</meaning>
          <type>math</type>
          <alttext>aC = xC</alttext>
          <latex>a_{\text{C}}=x_{\text{C}}</latex>
        </item>
        <item>
          <alttext>fB = 1</alttext>
          <latex>f_{\text{B}}=1</latex>
        </item>
        <item>
          <alttext>fC = 1</alttext>
          <latex>f_{\text{C}}=1</latex>
        </item>
        <item>
          <alttext>aB</alttext>
          <latex>a_{\text{B}}</latex>
        </item>
        <item>
          <alttext>fB</alttext>
          <latex>f_{\text{B}}</latex>
        </item>
      </math>
      <sources>
        <item>PAC, 1994, 66, 533. 'Standard quantities in chemical thermodynamics. Fugacities, activities and equilibrium constants for pure and mixed phases (IUPAC Recommendations 1994)' on page 543 (https://doi.org/10.1351/pac199466030533)</item>
      </sources>
    </item>
  </definitions>
